@grunweg I totally agree with the general point you're making, that squeezing terminal simps can cause issues with robustness; but I think this particular line (which was one of my suggestions above) is an exception to the general rule. 

Squeezing `simp [foo, bar]` to `simp only [foo, bar, baz]` does indeed make the code less robust, since it is vulnerable to breakage if the name of `baz` changes. However, if un-squeezed `simp` doesn't find _any_ of the correct lemmas – as in this case – then it seems to me that it's equally robust with or without the `only`; both `simp [foo, bar]` and `simp only [foo, bar]` will break if `foo` or `bar` changes – and the `only` version is faster. Wouldn't you agree?

(With apologies to @kebekus for hijacking his PR with a lengthy debate about such a minor code-hygiene point.)
